{"title_page": "Rodney Sturdee", "text_new": "[[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)| Rear Admiral]] '''Arthur Rodney Barry Sturdee''' [[Order of the Bath|CB]] [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|DSO]] (6 December 1919 \u2013 6 October 2009) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer who saw active service in the Second World War on HMS ''Exeter'' and in minesweepers and ended his career as Flag Officer, Gibraltar.\n==Life==\nThe son of a naval officer, Commander Barry Victor Sturdee,<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rear-admiral-rodney-sturdee-flag-officer-gibraltar-1969-72-5660ml2p6h8 Rear Admiral Rodney Sturdee: Flag Officer Gibraltar 1969 72] (obituary) in [[The Times]], 5 November 2009, accessed 17 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> whose father had been a Church of England clergyman in Devon and a first cousin of [[Admiral of the Fleet]] [[Doveton Sturdee|Sir Doveton Sturdee]],<ref> [http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Barry_Victor_Sturdee Barry Victor Sturdee] at dreadnoughtproject.org, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> the young Sturdee was educated at the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]], passing out on 1 September 1938, at the age of eighteen, and joining the Royal Navy as a [[midshipman]].<ref>The Navy List 1938, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CXcTAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA230#v=onepage&q&f=false  p. 230</ref> [[File:HMS Exeter (68) off Coco Solo c1939.jpg|thumb|HMS Exeter]] When war with Germany broke out the next year, Sturdee was serving in the South Atlantic on the [[York-class cruiser]] [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS ''Exeter'']], which had been sent to help the survivors of an earthquake in [[Chile]]. His ship was conveniently placed to be sent to take part in the [[Battle of the River Plate]] of December 1939 and was badly damaged by enemy fire.<ref name=times/> She then steamed for the [[Falkland Islands]], where she stayed for several weeks to make repairs.<ref>M. J. Whitley, ''Cruisers of World War Two An International Encyclopedia'' (London: Cassell, 1995), p. 95</ref> On 29 February 1940, with [[F. S. Bell|Captain F. S. Bell]] and other officers and men of ''Exeter'', Sturdee was given the [[Freedom of the City]] of [[Exeter]], when they marched through the streets with the ship\u2019s shell-torn [[White Ensign]], welcomed by a crowd of 50,000.<ref name=cornforth>David Cornforth, [http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/EM/otherexeters.html Royal Navy Ships Named HMS Exeter] (2005) at Exeter Memories, [https://web.archive.org/web/20070625021302/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/otherexeters.html archived here]</ref>\n[[File:HMS Algerine FL472.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Algerine'']]\nSturdee was promoted to Sub-Lieutenant in January 1941, and Lieutenant a month later.<ref name=unithistories> [https://www.unithistories.com/officers/RN_officersS3.html STURDEE Arthur Rodney Barry\u201d] at unithistories.com, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> He was transferred to service in the [[Algerine-class minesweeper|''Algerine''-class]] [[minesweeper]]s [[HMS Fly|HMS ''Fly'']], ''St Kilda, Albacore, Squall, Waterwitch, Cadmus, Nimbus, Stornoway, Acute'' and ''Brave'',<ref> [http://www.mcdoa.org.uk/ww_ii_awards_for_rn_minesweeping_S.htm WW II Awards for RN Minesweeping - MCDOA] at mcdoa.org.uk, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> and on 12 June 1945 was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for his work in arduous minesweeping operations on the coasts of Italy. The citation read \u201cfor skill, perseverance and great devotion to duty\u201d.<ref name=times/> From July to September 1945, he was posted to an onshore navigation course, and then in September rejoined HMS ''Fly'' as Navigating Officer.<ref name=unithistories/>\n\nSturdee was promoted to Lieutenant-Commander in February 1949, Commander in December 1952, Captain in June 1960, and Rear Admiral on 7 July 1969,<ref name=unithistories/> ending his naval career as [[British Forces Gibraltar#Administration|Flag Officer]], [[Gibraltar]], from October 1969 to January 1972,<ref name=times/> with the further title of Admiral Superintendant, [[Gibdock|HM Dockyard, Gibraltar]].<ref>[[Jane's Fighting Ships]] (Sampson Low, Marston and Company, 1969), p. 304</ref>\n\nOn 7 April 1972, Sturdee retired from the navy to his native [[Worcestershire]]<ref name=times/> and soon took up a new job as bursar at [[Malvern Girls College]], which lasted until 1985. He was president of the Worcestershire branch of the [[Royal British Legion]] and also of the Malvern Sea Cadets.<ref name=gazette>[https://www.malverngazette.co.uk/news/malvern/4702437.navy-man-enjoyed-distinguished-career/ \u201cNavy man enjoyed distinguished career\u201d] in ''[[Malvern Gazette]]'', 26 October 2009</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1953, Sturdee married firstly in [[Mulhouse]], [[Alsace]], Marie-Claire Amstoutz, whom he met while she was working at the [[Embassy of France, London|French Embassy in London]]. They had a son and a daughter, Dominique and Christopher. His first wife died in 1995, and in 2001, at the age of 81, Sturdee married secondly, a widow with a daughter, and they lived together at Castlemorton Common in the [[Malvern Hills]] until his death.<ref name=gazette/>\n\n==Honours==\n*Concepcion Award (Chile), 24 January 1939<ref name=unithistories/>\n*[[Freedom of the City]] of [[Exeter]], 29 February 1940<ref name=cornforth/>\n*Distinguished Service Cross, 1945<ref name=times/>\n*[[Companion of the Order of the Bath]], June 1971<ref>Supplement to [[The London Gazette]], 12 June 1971, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/45384/supplement/5958/data.pdf p. 5958]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sturdee, Arthur Rodney Barry}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n", "text_old": "[[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)| Rear Admiral]] '''Arthur Rodney Barry Sturdee''' [[Order of the Bath|CB]] [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|DSO]] (6 December 1919 \u2013 6 October 2009) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer who saw active service in the Second World War on HMS ''Exeter'' and in minesweepers and ended his career as Flag Officer, Gibraltar.\n==Life==\nThe son of a naval officer, Commander Barry Victor Sturdee,<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rear-admiral-rodney-sturdee-flag-officer-gibraltar-1969-72-5660ml2p6h8 Rear Admiral Rodney Sturdee: Flag Officer Gibraltar 1969 72] (obituary) in [[The Times]], 5 November 2009, accessed 17 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> whose father had been a Church of England clergyman in Devon anc a first cousin of [[Admiral of the Fleet]] [[Doveton Sturdee|Sir Doveton Sturdee]],<ref> [http://www.dreadnoughtproject.org/tfs/index.php/Barry_Victor_Sturdee Barry Victor Sturdee] at dreadnoughtproject.org, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> the young Sturdee was educated at the [[Britannia Royal Naval College|Royal Naval College, Dartmouth]], passing out on 1 September 1938, at the age of eighteen, and joining the Royal Navy as a [[midshipman]].<ref>The Navy List 1938, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CXcTAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA230#v=onepage&q&f=false  p. 230</ref> [[File:HMS Exeter (68) off Coco Solo c1939.jpg|thumb|HMS Exeter]] When war with Germany broke out the next year, Sturdee was serving in the South Atlantic on the [[York-class cruiser]] [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS ''Exeter'']], which had been sent to help the survivors of an earthquake in [[Chile]]. His ship was conveniently placed to be sent to take part in the [[Battle of the River Plate]] of December 1939 and was badly damaged by enemy fire.<ref name=times/> She then steamed for the [[Falkland Islands]], where she stayed for several weeks to make repairs.<ref>M. J. Whitley, ''Cruisers of World War Two An International Encyclopedia'' (London: Cassell, 1995), p. 95</ref> On 29 February 1940, with [[F. S. Bell|Captain F. S. Bell]] and other officers and men of ''Exeter'', Sturdee was given the [[Freedom of the City]] of [[Exeter]], when they marched through the streets with the ship\u2019s shell-torn [[White Ensign]], welcomed by a crowd of 50,000.<ref name=cornforth>David Cornforth, [http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/EM/otherexeters.html Royal Navy Ships Named HMS Exeter] (2005) at Exeter Memories, [https://web.archive.org/web/20070625021302/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/otherexeters.html archived here]</ref>\n[[File:HMS Algerine FL472.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Algerine'']]\nSturdee was promoted to Sub-Lieutenant in January 1941, and Lieutenant a month later.<ref name=unithistories> [https://www.unithistories.com/officers/RN_officersS3.html STURDEE Arthur Rodney Barry\u201d] at unithistories.com, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> He was transferred to service in the [[Algerine-class minesweeper|''Algerine''-class]] [[minesweeper]]s [[HMS Fly|HMS ''Fly'']], ''St Kilda, Albacore, Squall, Waterwitch, Cadmus, Nimbus, Stornoway, Acute'' and ''Brave'',<ref> [http://www.mcdoa.org.uk/ww_ii_awards_for_rn_minesweeping_S.htm WW II Awards for RN Minesweeping - MCDOA] at mcdoa.org.uk, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> and on 12 June 1945 was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for his work in arduous minesweeping operations on the coasts of Italy. The citation read \u201cfor skill, perseverance and great devotion to duty\u201d.<ref name=times/> From July to September 1945, he was posted to an onshore navigation course, and then in September rejoined HMS ''Fly'' as Navigating Officer.<ref name=unithistories/>\n\nSturdee was promoted to Lieutenant-Commander in February 1949, Commander in December 1952, Captain in June 1960, and Rear Admiral on 7 July 1969,<ref name=unithistories/> ending his naval career as [[British Forces Gibraltar#Administration|Flag Officer]], [[Gibraltar]], from October 1969 to January 1972,<ref name=times/> with the further title of Admiral Superintendant, [[Gibdock|HM Dockyard, Gibraltar]].<ref>[[Jane's Fighting Ships]] (Sampson Low, Marston and Company, 1969), p. 304</ref>\n\nOn 7 April 1972, Sturdee retired from the navy to his native [[Worcestershire]]<ref name=times/> and soon took up a new job as bursar at [[Malvern Girls College]], which lasted until 1985. He was president of the Worcestershire branch of the [[Royal British Legion]] and also of the Malvern Sea Cadets.<ref name=gazette>[https://www.malverngazette.co.uk/news/malvern/4702437.navy-man-enjoyed-distinguished-career/ \u201cNavy man enjoyed distinguished career\u201d] in ''[[Malvern Gazette]]'', 26 October 2009</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1953, Sturdee married firstly in [[Mulhouse]], [[Alsace]], Marie-Claire Amstoutz, whom he met while she was working at the [[Embassy of France, London|French Embassy in London]]. They had a son and a daughter, Dominique and Christopher. His first wife died in 1995, and in 2001, at the age of 81, Sturdee married secondly, a widow with a daughter, and they lived together at Castlemorton Common in the [[Malvern Hills]] until his death.<ref name=gazette/>\n\n==Honours==\n*Concepcion Award (Chile), 24 January 1939<ref name=unithistories/>\n*[[Freedom of the City]] of [[Exeter]], 29 February 1940<ref name=cornforth/>\n*Distinguished Service Cross, 1945<ref name=times/>\n*[[Companion of the Order of the Bath]], June 1971<ref>Supplement to [[The London Gazette]], 12 June 1971, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/45384/supplement/5958/data.pdf p. 5958]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sturdee, Arthur Rodney Barry}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodney_Sturdee"}
{"title_page": "Thorganby railway station", "text_new": "{{Short description|Disused railway station in Thorganby, North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name = Thorganby\n| locale = [[Thorganby, North Yorkshire|Thorganby]]\n| borough = [[North Yorkshire]]\n| coordinates ={{coord|53.8595|-0.9709|type:landmark_region:GB_scale:2000_source:Google| display=inline, title}}\n| gridref  = SE677408\n| original = [[Derwent Valley Light Railway]]\n| platforms = 1\n| years = 29 October 1912\n| events = Opened to goods\n| years1 = 21 July 1913\n| events1 = Opened to passengers\n| years2 = 1 September 1926\n| events2 = Closed to passengers\n| years3 = {{End date|1968|12|31|df=y}}\n| events3 = Closed to goods\n}}\n'''Thorganby railway station''' served the village of [[Thorganby, North Yorkshire]], England from 1912 to 1964 on the [[Derwent Valley Light Railway]]. The station had services northwards to [[York]] ([[York (Layerthorpe) railway station|Layerthorpe railway station]]) and south to [[Cliffe Common]], which was a station on the line between [[Selby]] and [[Market Weighton]].\n\n== History ==\nWhilst the line was first proposed in 1898, it wasn't built until 1912. Thorganby station opened to passengers in July 1913, along with the other stations on the [[Derwent Valley Light Railway]], and it closed to passengers in 1926.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burgess |first1=Neil |title=The lost railways of Yorkshire's East Riding |date=2011 |publisher=Stenlake |location=Catrine |isbn=9781840335521 |page=32}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Quick |first1=Michael |title=Railway Passenger Stations in England, Scotland and Wales; a Chronology |url=https://rchs.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Railway-Passenger-Stations-v5.01-2.pdf |website=rchs.org.uk |accessdate=30 March 2020 |page=393 |format=PDF |date=2019}}</ref> However, it was opened for goods traffic in October 1912 from {{rws|Wheldrake}} south through Thorganby to {{rws|Cliffe Common}}.{{sfn|Young|2015|p=112}}\n\nThe station was {{convert|11.5|mi}} south of [[York (Layerthorpe) railway station|York Layerthorpe]] railway station (the line's terminus) and {{convert|4.5|mi}} north of the southern end of the line at Cliffe Common, though connections could be made there to {{rws|Selby}} railway station,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Body |first1=Geoffrey |title=Railways of the Eastern Region |date=1989 |publisher=P. Stephens |location=Cambridge |isbn=1-85260-072-1 |page=152}}</ref> which was on the line between Selby and Market Weighton.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hoole |first1=Ken |title=A regional history of the railways of Great Britain. Vol. 4, North East England |date=1974 |publisher=David & Charles |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-7153-6439-1 |page=63}}</ref> The station was {{convert|0.75|mi}} from the village of Thorganby, and was mainly built to encourage agricultural traffic.{{sfn|Young|2015|p=113}} During the passenger carrying era, the service pattern was typically three return trains per day, though delays were frequent as the trains were mixed passenger and goods, and this involved some shunting at stations.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Suggitt |first1=Gordon |title=Lost railways of North and East Yorkshire |date=2007 |publisher=Countryside Books |location=Newbury |isbn=978-1-85306-918-5 |page=127}}</ref>\n\nThe station at Thorganby was on the east side of the line and had just one platform, though a passing loop was installed immediately south of the station and the goods yard had four sidings.{{sfn|Young|2015|p=114}}\n\nComplete closure to freight came in December 1964; only the station building remains, which is in a derelict state,{{sfn|Young|2015|p=111}} however, the stationmasters house survives as a private dwelling.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jefferson-Brown |first1=Nadia |title=This one's been sealed |url=https://infoweb.newsbank.com/apps/news/document-view?p=AWNB&t=&sort=YMD_date%3AD&page=1&fld-base-0=alltext&maxresults=20&val-base-0=Thorganby%20railway&docref=news/1119141FEC2CC478 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=infoweb.newsbank.com |date=11 May 2006|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book |last1=Young |first1=Alan |title=Lost Stations of Yorkshire; the North and East Ridings |date=2015 |publisher=Silver Link |location=Kettering |isbn=978-1-85794-453-2 |ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/4528722 Geograph image of station building]\n\n{{Historical Rail Start}}\n{{rail line |previous={{rws|Cottingwith}}<br><small>Line private, station closed</small>|next={{rws|Skipwith}}<br><small>Line private, station closed</small>|route=[[Derwent Valley Light Railway]]|col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1912]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1926]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1968 disestablishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Disused railway station in Thorganby, North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name = Thorganby\n| locale = [[Thorganby, North Yorkshire|Thorganby]]\n| borough = [[North Yorkshire]]\n| coordinates ={{coord|53.8595|-0.9709|type:landmark_region:GB_scale:2000_source:Google| display=inline, title}}\n| gridref  = SE677408\n| original = [[Derwent Valley Light Railway]]\n| platforms = 1\n| years = 29 October 1912\n| events = Opened to goods\n| years1 = 21 July 1913\n| events1 = Opened to passengers\n| years2 = 1 September 1926\n| events2 = Closed to passengers\n| years3 = {{End date|1968|12|31|df=y}}\n| events3 = Closed to goods\n}}\n'''Thorganby railway station''' served the village of [[Thorganby, North Yorkshire]], England from 1912 to 1964 on the [[Derwent Valley Light Railway]]. The station had services northwards to [[York]] ([[York (Layerthorpe) railway station|Layerthorpe railway station]]) and south to [[Cliffe Common]], which was a station on the line between [[Selby]] and [[Market Weighton]].\n\n== History ==\nWhilst the line was first proposed in 1898, it wasn't built until 1912. Thorganby station opened to passengers in July 1913, along with the other stations on the [[Derwent Valley Light Railway]], and it closed to passengers in 1926.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burgess |first1=Neil |title=The lost railways of Yorkshire's East Riding |date=2011 |publisher=Stenlake |location=Catrine |isbn=9781840335521 |page=32}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Quick |first1=Michael |title=Railway Passenger Stations in England, Scotland and Wales; a Chronology |url=https://rchs.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Railway-Passenger-Stations-v5.01-2.pdf |website=rchs.org.uk |accessdate=30 March 2020 |page=393 |format=PDF |date=2019}}</ref> However, it was opened for goods traffic in October 1912 from {{rws|Wheldrake}} south through Thorganby to {{rws|Cliffe Common}}.{{sfn|Young|2015|p=112}}\n\nThe station was {{convert|11.5|mi}} south of [[York (Layerthorpe) railway station|York Layerthorpe]] railway station (the line's terminus) and {{convert|4.5|mi}} north of the southern end of the line at Cliffe Common, though connections could be made there to {{rws|Selby}} railway station,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Body |first1=Geoffrey |title=Railways of the Eastern Region |date=1989 |publisher=P. Stephens |location=Cambridge |isbn=1-85260-072-1 |page=152}}</ref> which was on the line between Selby and Market Weighton.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hoole |first1=Ken |title=A regional history of the railways of Great Britain. Vol. 4, North East England |date=1974 |publisher=David & Charles |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-7153-6439-1 |page=63}}</ref> The station was {{convert|0.75|mi}} from the village of Thorganby, and was mainly built to encourage agricultural traffic.{{sfn|Young|2015|p=113}} During the passenger carrying era, the service pattern was typically three return trains per day, though delays were frequent as the trains were mixed passenger and goods, and this involved some shunting at stations.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Suggitt |first1=Gordon |title=Lost railways of North and East Yorkshire |date=2007 |publisher=Countryside Books |location=Newbury |isbn=978-1-85306-918-5 |page=127}}</ref>\n\nThe station at Thorganby was on the east side of the line and had just one platform, though a passing loop was installed immediately south of the station and the goods yard had four sidings.{{sfn|Young|2015|p=114}}\n\nComplete closure to freight came in December 1964; only the station building remains, which is in a derelict state,{{sfn|Young|2015|p=111}} howver, the stationmasters house survives as a private dwelling.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jefferson-Brown |first1=Nadia |title=This one's been sealed |url=https://infoweb.newsbank.com/apps/news/document-view?p=AWNB&t=&sort=YMD_date%3AD&page=1&fld-base-0=alltext&maxresults=20&val-base-0=Thorganby%20railway&docref=news/1119141FEC2CC478 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=infoweb.newsbank.com |date=11 May 2006|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book |last1=Young |first1=Alan |title=Lost Stations of Yorkshire; the North and East Ridings |date=2015 |publisher=Silver Link |location=Kettering |isbn=978-1-85794-453-2 |ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/4528722 Geograph image of station building]\n\n{{Historical Rail Start}}\n{{rail line |previous={{rws|Cottingwith}}<br><small>Line private, station closed</small>|next={{rws|Skipwith}}<br><small>Line private, station closed</small>|route=[[Derwent Valley Light Railway]]|col={{NER colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1912]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1926]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1968 disestablishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thorganby_railway_station"}
